</taxonomicName>
is the most widespread species of the genus, its distribution ranging from North 
<collectingCountry id="F3723BA4C21E2812FDD5BDBF7C2865CF" box="[530,582,1237,1259]" name="India" pageId="1" pageNumber="1198">India</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F3723BA4C21E2812FD44BDBF7CD165CF" box="[643,703,1237,1259]" name="Nepal" pageId="1" pageNumber="1198">Nepal</collectingCountry>
across 
<collectingCountry id="F3723BA4C21E2812FCD0BDBF7D3265CE" box="[791,860,1237,1258]" name="Myanmar" pageId="1" pageNumber="1198">Burma</collectingCountry>
to South 
<collectingCountry id="F3723BA4C21E2812FC17BDBF7A6265CF" box="[976,1036,1237,1259]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="1198">China</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F3723BA4C21E2812FF75BD987F62642C" box="[178,268,1266,1288]" name="Thailand" pageId="1" pageNumber="1198">Thailand</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="135E67B1C21E2812FEDEBD987F31642C" box="[281,351,1266,1288]" captionStart="Map 2" captionStartId="3.[178,223,897,918]" captionTargetBox="[178,1083,212,872]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1083,212,872]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Map 2: Distributions of Sclerochiton indicus (black circles), S. penicillatus (white triangles), and S. bistipulatus (white circles)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415818" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415818/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="1198">Map 2</figureCitation>
